   Hmm zanchief...  We could probably go around and around on the issue of why I started smoking...  It's basically pointless to go there.<br>
<br>
   However, I would state that the 'kick in the right direction' is improper.  Firstly, it is NOT ILLEGAL for him to smoke cigarettes.  If it WERE illegal, I can definetly see reason to punish him to get him to stop doing illegal things...  HOWEVER at this time, it is not illegal.  As such, I fully expect that the school system NOT take the law into it's own hands and deny a child an education solely on the principle that what he is doing is unhealthy.<br>
<br>
   Ya know, MABYE the 'health' class that teaches more explicitly why smoking is bad for you happens on one of those 3 days he was suspended on.<br>
<br>
   This method of punishment to yeild positive results (rehabilitation) has already been proven INEFFECTIVE AT BEST.  Take a look at the prison system and the number of repeat offenders.  Punishment does nothing to prevent future discresions.  Only education seems to help, yet you deny this ''offender'' the education he requires to get himself outa the unhealthy habit of smoking?<br>
<br>
   Perhaps they should come up with other methods.  Methods that simply embaressed the student...  In school suspension is a pretty effective tool at doing this.<br>
<br>
   The school system has NO right to deny someone an education because he or she has habits which may or may not be considered less than healthy.<br>
